            ">The Internet made everyone get these viral products</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-spacer height="18px"></mj-spacer>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Fire meets PR</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           The viral Stanley Cup is a product from a company that was founded way back in 1913. Stanley has always been known for its rugged, steel-insulated gear, which workers and campers used. However, the well-renowned <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-02-08-2025-40-oz-quencher-tumbler" target="_blank">40 oz Quencher tumbler</a> was launched in 2016 and flopped big time. It didn’t perform well in traditional retail, and trade was so poor that it was nearly discontinued.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/lainey-wilson-watermelon-moonshine-quencher-collab.jpg" alt="The brand launched its first celebrity collaboration with the country musician Lainey Wilson, who produced a pink-and-green Watermelon Moonshine Quencher" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i> The brand launched its first collaboration with the country musician Lainey Wilson, who produced a pink-and-green Watermelon Moonshine Quencher. Credits: Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Then came the moment that set the internet ablaze. A <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-02-08-2025-tiktok-video" target="_blank">TikTok video</a> went viral in 2023 featuring a woman whose Kia Sorento had been destroyed in a car fire. Everything in the car was reduced to ash except her Stanley Quencher. The company’s CEO posted a response acknowledging the video and offering to get the woman a car. His post was widely applauded online, and suddenly, Stanley gained traction and eventually became iconic.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Stanley capitalized on the hype by targeting TikTok moms and influencers. When women said, "<i>We love this cup and here’s why</i>," the brand pivoted and provided exactly what the customer wanted and more. They focused on exclusive color drops, social media engagement, and scarcity-based hype. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Currently, Stanley has grown into a nearly $ 750M annual business, up from around $70–94M in 2019–2020. </p>
        </mj-text>
